Civilian Drone Strike Murders have Increased as Years Have Gone On, Independent of Drone Strike Counts: Exploring the Data Science Pipeline Through Confirmed US Drone Strikes in Afghanistan, Pakistan, Somalia, and Yemen (2010-2020)¶

By Aaron Hetzer¶

In this notebook we will present data that suggests that the murder of innocent civilians in US drone strikes and other military operations have not only increased as years have gone on, but have increased independent of the number of drone strike counts. This leads us to the conclusion that US efforts to improve collateral civilian murders have either been incompetent or non-existent. Thus the only way to avoid civilian drone strike deaths is to stop using drones to kill people in Afghanistan, Pakistan, Somalia, and Yemen.

We will also use our analysis of this data set as a tutorial to describe the data science pipeline. In this, be on the look out for actional insights in your own data science presented in bold.

This pipeline will include:

  1. Data collection - Using The Bureau of Investigative Journalism's 2010-2020 Drone Warfare Project's CSV
  2. Data Management - Getting our collected "Drone Warfare" data in a useable form
  3. Exploratory Analysis - What can we figure out by looking at our managed data
  4. Hypothesis Testing, and Analysis
  5. Conclusions of insights gained - Civilian Drone Strike Murders have Increased as Years Have Gone On, Independent of Drone Strike Counts

1. Data collection - Using The Bureau of Investigative Journalism's 2010-2020 Drone Warfare Project's CSV¶

Every data science project requires a dataset to examine. How you collect a dataset will depend upon its availability.

We will use The Bureau of Investigative Journalism's Drone Warfare Project as our primary data source for discussing US drone strikes in Afghanistan, Pakistan, Yemen, and Somalia between 2010 and the project's end in 2020.

The Bureau of Investigative Journalism (TBIJ) provides its data to the public through a collection of Google Sheets pages. We want as much information as possible to start out with. So we are going to focus on each country's "full database" Google Sheets page. TBIJ has data on drone strikes in Afghanistan, Pakistan, Somalia, and Yemen.

Choosing What "Drone Warfare" Data to Use¶

When examining each country's respective pages, we will note that there are several sheets in each spreadsheet. Many of these are summary, or visual representations of the data. Although, Afghanistan's Google Sheets page has a variety of sheets with useful information, we will focus on the sheet that contain data shared by all four countries. That is, the sheet that has US drone strike information on it.

To start collecting our own data, we will begin by creating a class, Drone_Data, to collect the information associated with each country. We are chosing to use a class rather than another data structure because its flexibility allows for us to store several different datatypes which, during the initialization process, can be used to perform operations on without having to repeat code.

Extracting Data from Google Sheets¶

Data from Google Sheets is ultimately formated as a Comma Separated Values (CSV). CSV can be extracted into a pandas.DataFrame using the pandas.read_CSV(...) function.

pandas.read_CSV(...) can read a URL if the URL is passes through a CSV. So we need to make sure that we use the "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/{self.page_id}/export?gid={self.sheet_id}&format=csv" URL format to export the specific sheet we want as a CSV.

The sheet_id and page_id are part of the standard URL. We will create a Drone_Data class that takes this information in as initializing parameters. This will allow us to easily create objects, and go ahead and initialize the pandas.DataFrame associated with each country's dataset once we import the data. The ease of use associated with creating a class to work with objects programmatically makes it more desirable than using some data structures to store this information.

Why are we using a pandas.DataFrame?¶

A pandas.DataFrame is a very useful data structure for data science. A pandas.DataFrame is a two-dimentional data structure similar to a table, or a SQL relation. They have row and column indexes, and columns can have different data types. Note that if you are used to SQL, what is called a key in SQL is called an "index" in pandas.DataFrame.

pandas.DataFrame are so useful because we do not need to iterate through entries to perform operations on them. Instead, we can perform operations directly on the columns (which are pandas.Series). This results in (subjectively) easier to write code and faster operations.

If you want to learn more about pandas.DataFrame, be sure to look at the documentation.

In [2]:
# Note that every Google Sheets spreadsheet has a page_id, which comes after "/d/"
# in the original URL, and a sheet_id, which comes after "gid" in the original URL

class Drone_Data:
    def __init__(self, name, sheet_id, page_id):
        self.name = name
        self.sheet_id = sheet_id
        self.page_id = page_id
        # These sheet_id and page_id will be our user inputed initialization values that
        # we can then use to build our extract_url. 
        self.extract_url = \
            f"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/{self.page_id}/export?gid={self.sheet_id}&format=csv"
        # Read the CSV we can get from extract_url into a pandas DataFrame 
        self.df = pd.read_csv(self.extract_url)

The Bureau of Investigative Journalism's 2010-2020 Drone Warfare Project's Data Collection¶

Between 2010 and 2020, The Bureau of Investigative Journalism (TBIJ) "tracked US drone strikes and other covert actions in Pakistan, Afghanistan, Yemen and Somalia." To this end, they used "thousands of press reports filed by reputable national and international media outlets," data provided by NATO and other US-led or US sources, three field investigations, legal cases, leaked information and more to compile its data over the lifetime of the project.

Limitations of the "Drone Warefare" dataset¶

The Bureau of Investigative Journalism (TBIJ)'s variety of sources alongside the US' interests in keeping strategic and tactical information secret and civilian death's undercounted means that TBIJ's results are necessarily incomplete.

As they point out in Yemen, for instance, "[i]t is often unclear who is responsible for attacks or even whether it is the work of a manned plane or a drone although airstrikes are routinely described as drone strikes in news reporting." In Afghanistan, they have a different problem: it often took more than a day to get drone strike information to journalists. By the time they recieved this information, there would be so much breaking news that this resulted in "notably undercounted" data in the country. The timeline

Furthermore, TBIJ points out that there can be contradictory information reported about the number of deaths. While they updated their counts as new information was released, this results in a reported range wherein the minimum remains the same and the maximum number changes to include new potential information.

It is also notable that each country's respective datasets differ with regards to time frame, data collected, and data availability. This is reflected in both the number of observations, and the number of possible values.

Despite these limitations, TBIJ remains an exceedingly comprehensive source for information on US drone strike in Afghanistan, Pakistan, Yemen, and Somalia from 2010-2020.

Other forms of data collection¶

Not all data will exist in a Google Sheets page. We saw above how we could use the pandas.read_csv function to extract CSV from a URL to a DataFrame. We could also store a CSV locally, and access it using the same pandas.read_csv function, but with its file path instead of the URL.

pandas provides a number of methods similar to that lets one read formatted information directly into a DataFrame. There is a good chance that if you have some common formated data, pandas has a method to allow you to collect it into a DataFrame. Be sure to read the pandas documentation for a full list and explanation of methods allowing one to read an Excel file, SQL tables, JSON formated data and more into a pandas.DataFrames.

Another way to access an existing dataset is through a website's API. An API (Application Programming Interface) allows you to ask a server for information they already have stored in a database. If the request (or "query") is in a valid form with the necessary credentials, then it should return the information asked for in a structured document. You can frequently access APIs through python's requests module. This module allows one to make HTTP requests. One common form of API is a REST API.

Unfortunately, many websites do not have APIs, or APIs that have all the information that you want to get. If you still need to get a dataset from a website in these cases, you may need to "scrape" the information from the HTML and/or CSS on the page. This process is called web scrapping. BeautifulSoup is package commonly used for scraping and parsing HTML data. It's documentation can be found here. You can find out more information about web-scrapping here.

2. Data Management - Getting our collected "Drone Warfare" data in a useable form¶

We've already begun managing our "Drone Warfare" dataset by importing them into pandas.DataFrames. But, at this point, each country's dataset are separate attributes of their respective Drone_Data object. It might be good to keep their separate pandas.DataFrames for later.

We want to begin by looking for trends, or clues to dig into across the whole dataset. This is called the "Exploratory data Analysis" part of the pipeline (more on that later). Before we can do this sort of broad analysis, however, we'll want to combine all of our data in one pandas.DataFrame.

We could naively combine each conutry's Drone_Data.df. But it's important to be familiar with your dataset before we begin managing it. Familiarizing oneself with the dataset can help guide analytic decisions, avoid unncessary pitfalls, and make choices with managing the dataset.

Let's begin by taking a look at what kind of overlap we already have:

shared_columns = afghanistan_strikes.df.columns.intersection(yemen_strikes.df.columns) \

So if we take the data as given to us, only the Date and Strike link columns are shared between each country's DataFrame.

First, we will convert the Date column from a string to a datetime object. This allows for easier manipulation of the date.

We will also go ahead and extract the year from this object into its own column. This is so that we can use it as a "bucket value" later on. A "bucket value," or "bin" refers to a group of data that share some characteristic. Binning information can be useful when there is a "noisy" continuous variable, like month and day for change over time. If you're more interested in binning, check out this StackOverflow answer.

# Create a new DataFrame to store our combined data in
all_countries_strikes_df = pd.DataFrame()

# Variable used to track total length of original DataFrames
total_df_len = 0

# For each of our countries, we will add the length of it to total_df_len for a later confirmation
# Then, we will concat these values to the all_countries_strikes_df DataFrame. Concat allows us to
# combine DataFrames. 
# We are choosing the axis=0 keyword so that we are combining our rows, and the
# ignore_index=True keyword so that we do not align the columns on the rows we already have in DataFrame.
# Note that we are using the .reset_index() method on our second concatinated term to ensure that our index
# is numerical and can thusly be added to all_countries_strikes_df consistently.
for country in country_list:
    total_df_len += len(country.df.index)
    all_countries_strikes_df = pd.concat([all_countries_strikes_df, country.df.reset_index()], 
                                         axis=0, ignore_index=True)

Let's do a quick sanity check on this master DataFrame to ensure that we didn't accidently drop any rows in our concatination. To this end, we'll compare the sum of all of the individual dataframe's lengths to the total DataFrame's length to accomplish this.

As a data scientist, small checks small sanity checks like this throughout your code can help you catch issues as they arise. For instance, if we were to need to do SQL style merges to combine data frames, it could have been very easy to accidentally drop columns or rows--especially for complicated merges.

Dialectics of Data Science: Returning to previous steps in the pipeline¶

There are a three columns titled Unnamed: x, with different integer values in "x". It's not very clear what they are from looking at our DataFrame alone. So we'll need take a look at the original data again.

This dialectic movement between data collection and data management is an important part of the data science pipeline. As we comb through our data, we may have questions that our data alone cannot answer. We often need to add context, and sometimes even need to collect more data. This dialectical movement occurs throughout the pipeline. In this sense, "pipeline" is perhaps a flawed metaphor for trying to answer a question using data science. It implies that we are only moving in one direction, like water flowing down, or up a pipe. Instead, it's more like a set of data science "see saws" wherein movement in one part of the process will influence movement needed for another part.

In your own data science work, it is important to recognize, at each step (i.e. not just the data management step) when to look at previous steps and see how returning to them can help strengthen your work.

With this in mind, when we look at how Unnamed: x is used in the original datasets on Google Sheets, we'll note that for the Afghanistan, and Pakistan Drone Warfare data they refer to an "index" value internal to The Bureau of Investigative Journalism (TBIJ). There is not an unnamed column in the Somalia data set. Finally, the Yemen data set's "Unnamed: x" contains an occational dead link to a TBIJ article.

Since we are not interested in doing data science on TBIJ's coverage of these articles, the data stored in these columns is largely vestigial. We can drop their respective columns:

In [14]:
# Note that you can pass in a list like set into the drop function, 
# we are specifying that we want specific columns dropped with the columns keyword
all_countries_strikes_df.drop(columns=["Unnamed: 19", "Unnamed: 18", "Unnamed: 13"], inplace=True)

Tidying Data¶

Another way in which we can manage our data is through Tidy Data. Hadley Wickham defines tidying data as "structuring datasets to facilitate analysis." According to Wickham, tidy data must pertain to a specific structure: "each variable is a column, each observation is a row, and each type of observational unit is a table."

If the ultimate goal of tidying is to "facilitate analysis" you should consider the usefulness of tidying for your specific data set. For instance, our "Drone Warfare" data is a bit strange with regards to tidying. Let's take a look:

Tidying 1: "Each variable is a column"¶

If each variable is a column then we have several columns that may be combined. For instance, any of the columns that have "minimum" and "maximums" prefixes could be combined to represent a range.

However, there is an argument made that these are distinct variables. Once again, we should return to our original dataset to help make our decision. According to The Bureau of Investigative Journalism (TBIJ) "credible sources differ over how many people were killed we provide a minimum and maximum count of the number of people reported killed." Elsewhere, the TBIJ methodology page notes the minimum numbers are "unchanged," while the maximum was updated over time. This means that each "maximum" prefix is actually the composite of a variable number of observations.

So, because there are different methods used to collect "minimum" and "maximum" data in the original set, I believe they should be considered different variables.

Tidying 2: "Each observation is a row"¶

Furthermore, we know that the ranges can't be segregated into equal sized bins because the maximum is uncertain. So it's possible that a value like the SOM003 strike on 09/01/2007 in Somalia which killed at least 4 people, but as many as 31 could fit in a variety of bins.

Thus, we don't have any great way of "tidying" our data with regards to the rows.

Melting DataFrames

Sometimes, observations are presented as columns. This results in what is called a "wide" table. If you want to make a wide pandas.DataFrame tidy, you can use the pandas.melt function. Users of pandas.melt will pass the method a DataFrame, and then identify a set of "one or more columns are identifier variables (id_vars)." These id_vars are kept as columns. The rest of the columns are known as measured variables (value_vars). Here's a useful for guide for using the melt function if you need to use it.

These value_vars columns are "unpivoted" by pandas.melt to become rows. The pivoted value_vars will retain whatever their original id_vars are in their new row.

Once a "wide" table is melted into a "long" table (also known as a "molten" table), it can be further manipulated into making each variable a column if necessary.

Tidying 3: "Each type of observational unit is a table"¶

This is a principle of Tidy Data that we can apply to our dataset! Specifically, we have a clear "death" observational type. This will include the following set of columns:

In [15]:
death_columns = ['Minimum total people killed', 'Maximum total people killed',

3. Exploratory Analysis - What can we figure out by looking at our managed data¶

So we've selected a data source, downloaded it, and managed our data to be in a usable form. Now what?

It can be difficult to decide what to look for in a dataset. Exploratory analysis can help us get a "feel" for the data set. We can use summary statistics (like mean, standard, deviation, sums, etc.) and visualizations to identify trends, problems, skew, and other relations that are imminent in our dataset.

We can use such relationships to form a hypothesis around. This hypothesis will lead us into Hypothesis testing. But, because our data is dialectic we may decided that we need to manage our data in a different way to learn more, returning to step 2, or that we need to collect more data, returning to step 1.

We'll begin by looking at some summary statistics for our dataset:

Summary statistics - descriptive statistics¶

We can use summary statistics to describe sets of data in simpler terms. This is a part of descriptive statistics. The pandas.DataFrame.describe() give such statistics for a given DataFrame or Dataframe column. According to the documentation these statistics include: "count, mean, std, min, max as well as lower, [median] and upper percentiles. By default the lower percentile is 25 and the upper percentile is 75. The 50 percentile is the same as the median."

We need to call describe() on a column that has numerical data for to return summary statistics. This seems to fit the "death" information contained in our death_df DataFrame which looks at all of our countries.

Summary statistics - correlative description¶

Another form of summary statistics you can use in your exploratory analysis are correlative descriptions. Correlative descriptions allow us to compare two variables and seek trends between them. Correlation refers to when two variables, we'll call them $X$ and $Y$ vary together.

But, as the famous saying goes "correlation does not equal causation." This means that correlation may reveal some sort of significant movement through a statistical relationship between $X$ and $Y$. But it also could mean that this is a "third term" that isn't considered that cause similar movement in $X$ and $Y$, while your $X$ and $Y$ are not actually reflecting one another. This third term influencing $X$ and $Y$ may also be called a confounding variable.

As such, its important to consider how strong of claims you can make surrounding correlative descriptions.

For our Drone Warfare dataset, we'll begin by comparing time to each country's respective "Minimum total people killed" and "Maximum total people killed" columns.

Covariance¶

Covariance between $X$ and $Y$ is represented by the formula:

$$cov(x,y) = \frac{1}{n} \sum^{n}_{i=1}(x_i-\bar{x})(y_i-\bar{y})$$

In this formula $n$ refers to the number of entries, $\bar{x}$ and $\bar{y}$ refer to the respective means of $x$ and $y$. We can note that a positive correlation, or a correlation wherein $X$ and $Y$ increase in the same direction as one another is reflected by a positive $cov(x,y)$. In contrast, a negative correlation, or a correlation wherein $X$ and $Y$ increase in opposite directions as one another is reflected by a negative $cov(x,y)$. This also implies that a $cov(x,y)$ near $0$ means that there is no strong relationship between $X$ and $Y$.

In pandas covariance is pandas.DataFrame.cov function.

In [25]:
for country in country_list:

          country.df["Year"].cov(country.df["Minimum total people killed"]).astype(str))

'Okay, so now what?': When to stop exploring, and start analyzing.¶

It can be difficult to know when to end the Exploratory Analysis phase of the data pipeline. You can always play with your data more, and indeed, there may be more insight that you haven't gotten to yet that summary or correlative statistics can reveal.

But, like our dialectical return to the data collection, and data management stages, exploratory analysis can also be returned to as new information is revealed and broad summary insight is needed.

Once you land on a point that you believe is interesting, or promising, or you have a specific hypothesis you'd like to test you can begin to use more precise statistical tools, and move into the Hypothesis Testing phase.

Determining if the "Civilian Murder Differential" is related to "Date" seems like an interesting question. Let's use some analytic tools to determine if this is different than what is expected.

4. Hypothesis Testing, and Analysis¶

In Hypothesis Testing you are trying to determine how likely it is that a hypothesis is true. Instead, it tells you how likely the "status quo" is given the data.

This "status quo" is also known as the null hypothesis (or $H_0$). The null hypothesis represents the default position that we start from - that there is no significant difference between the observed data and the what we expect from the world.

In our example, our $H_0$ is that the "Civilian Murder Differential" stayed the same across time.

The null hypothesis is tested against the alternative hypothesis (or $H_1$). The alternative hypothesis represents a statement mutually exclusive from the null hypothesis.

In our example, our $H_1$ is that the "Civilian Murder Differential" decreased over time.

It's important to note that Hypothesis Testing doesn't prove that some new hypothesis is true, or even that the null hypothesis is true. It can only say that we are rejecting the null hypothesis, or failing to reject the null hypothesis (more on that here).

Okay, so now that we've determined the $H_0$ and $H_1$, we need to talk about how we are testing the $H_0$.

We can use p-values to test the probability of getting the null hypothesis. When you calculate your p-values, you are trying to determine what the probability is of getting our results assuming that $H_0$ is true. You can calculate a p-value by adding together the probability that random chance generated (1) the data, (2) something else that is equal in probability to the data, and (3) something else that is rarer than the data. For normally distributed values, you can use a density function.

The smaller a p-value is, the stronger our evidence is that we should reject the null hypothesis. A small p-value means that there is a small probability that the values that we observed would occur given our null hypothesis. So for our example, a small p-value would mean that there is a small probably that we would see the amount of decrease we've observed in the "Civilian Murder Differential" assuming that the there was no causal decrease in "Civilian Murder Differential".

In the social sciences, .05 or 5% is commonly considered a standard "low" p-value. But, as stated throughout this tutorial, our data must be considered dialectically. Does it make sense to have .05 as our break point? What is the difference between .05, .49, and .051 or even between .05 and .06? Every data set will have different answers for this question. Blindly using .05 can become problematic around these edge cases.

With that in mind, I believe that we should use .01 as our p-value. Recall from the data collection phase that the "maximum" prefix always refers to a sourced, but unconfirmed number. This is a number that can change, but is less "solid" than the "minimum" prefix. This assumes a level of variance in the data collection process that is reflected in the formation of our "Civilian Murder Differential." Thus a lower p-value, like 0.01 should be used to reflect the added noise of collecting sensitive data from sources of varying qualities.

But you may choose an entirely different p-value given your data set, data collection methods, and other factors. When in doubt, however, choose a p-value of .05.

So, we now have all the pieces needed for a hypothesis test. Let's collect them here:

$H_0$: "Civilian Murder Differential" stayed the same across time

$H_1$: "Civilian Murder Differential" decreased over time

target p-value: 0.01

With these pieces in place, we can now statistically test our null hypothesis. We will use the statsmodels module to accomplish our statistical tests. But another popular module that could be used is scipy. scipy is powerful package with many mathematical tools. It's documentation can be found here.

Specifically, we are interested in statsmodels's ztest function. A z-test is a test that compares the expected mean to the population mean. From this, we will calculate a z-score and p-value and compare the produced p-value to our target p-value.

There are several conditions one must meet before they can perform a z-test: (1) your dataset must be larger than 30 samples so as to be approximated by a standard distribution; (2) your data points must be independent; (3) your data should be randomly selected.

Let's make sure we can perform a z-test: (1) Our data has >30 samples in each country-based subset; (2) the deaths of civilians in one drone strike are independent from the deaths of civilians in another drone strike; and (3) we can assume that our data is randomly selected from the population of drone strikes by nature of the variability of the collection of sources.

So, we can use a t-test! Let's dive in:

In [29]:
p_value = 0.01

for country in country_list:
    # ztest will return a tuple where the z-score is stored in [0] 
    # and the p-value is stored in [1]
    ztest_result = ztest(country.df["Civilian Murder Differential"], alternative="smaller")
    ztest_decision = "fail to reject"
    sign = ">="
    
    print(f"{country.name}\'s z-score: {ztest_result[0]}")
    print(f"{country.name}\'s p-value: {ztest_result[1]}")
   
    # We are looking for greater than p_value because we are doing a two-sided ztest
    if ztest_result[1] < p_value:
        ztest_decision = "reject"
        sign = "<"
    print(f"Since {ztest_result[1]} {sign} {p_value} we {ztest_decision} the null hypothesis\n")

Our z-scores are so high, that I'm now curious if there is evidence that the "Civilian Murder Differential" , in fact, increased over time in our data sets. To check, we will do another z-test. That means we have new alternative hypothesis.

Our pieces needed for a hypothesis test are now:

$H_0$: "Civilian Murder Differential" stayed the same across time

$H_1$: "Civilian Murder Differential" increased over time

target p-value: 0.01

We can use the same code as above, but this time with the alternative keyword set to "larger":

5. Conclusions of insights gained - Civilian Drone Strike Murders have Increased as Years Have Gone On, Independent of Drone Strike Counts¶

In your own data science work, it's important to present actional insights in clear language based on the results. For instance:

So, we now know that there is a lack of significant correlation between drone strike numbers per year and civilian deaths, and the results of our z-test seem to suggest that civilian deaths from drone strikes didn't stay the same, or decrease (i.e. drones murdering civilians may have increased!) as the years went on.

Conclusion: The US Should leave the Middle East¶

With these two facts in mind, it seems as though civilian drone strike deaths have increased independent of the number of drone strikes called each year!

This means that, according to the TIJB Drone Warfare dataset, anything the U.S. government has done to mitigate civilian deaths with drone strikes have had no effect, and in fact the U.S.' imperial ventures in the Middle East have only increased in the amount of collateral civilian murders as time has gone on.

So either the U.S. is incompetent at reducing civilian drone strike deaths, they don't care about them, or they are actively or passively malicious toward civilians in "enemy" countries. Thus, the only way for the U.S. to ensure that such innocent civilians not get killed by drone strikes is to stop using their international death-pantopticon.
